Comparison of gCrisprTools and MAGeCK Target Identification in CRISPR screens

Russell Bainer

7/7/2016

Overview

This document clarifies the differences between MAGeCK and gCrisprTools that may be relevant to target detection in CRISPR screens. The following analyses were performed using a two-condition contrast comparing gRNA abundances and target representation in the Control Reference and Control Expansion samples. This comparison was selected because it contains meaningful signals in the context of minimal selective pressure and library distortion, and consequently should be well suited for analysis by the MAGeCK algorithm; unless otherwise stated, gCrisprTools was run using only P-values for ranking and disqualification, so as to closely mimic the MAGeCK approach.

In most cases, MAGeCK and gCrisprTools perform equivalently when selecting top candidates and disqualifying poor ones, but MAGeCK tends to assign more significant P-values to weak target hits than gCrisprTools. This is apparently due to differences between the gRNA P-values estimated by MAGeCK, which uses a standard Negative Binomial test, and those estimated by more complex modeling frameworks such as voom/limma or DESeq2.

Algorithmic Details

gCrisprTools and MAGeCK aggregate P-values in a broadly similar manner. Each algorithm performs some form of normalization, and then estimates the significance of the observed differences in each gRNA’s abundance to generate one-tailed P-values. Both methods then aggregate these gRNA-level signals to the gene level using Robust Rank Alpha Aggregation (RRA), a modification of the RRA algorithm.

In the RRA algorithm, the normalized gRNA signal ranks (e.g., gRNA rank/N, where N is the number of gRNAs in the screen) within each target are assigned P-values based on their overall ranking within the experiment and the distribution of the other observed gRNA signal ranks within that target. Specifically, each gRNA is assigned a P-value by comparing its normalized rank to a Beta distribution, appropriately parameterized for the gRNA signal’s rank within the target set and the total number of gRNAs associated with the target. The smallest observed gRNA P within the target set is reported as the target’s score, and these target-level scores are assigned a significance level via permutation of the gRNA labels.

Intuitively, the RRA score quanitfies the extent to which the ranks of the gRNAs associated with a target are skewed toward the top of the overall distribution by ordering the normalized ranks and then checking whether each successive value is consistent with random draws from a uniform distribution. It is possible for gRNA ranks to deviate from a uniform distribution in ways that are not of interest in the context of a screening experiment, however, and the modified RRAversion introduces a significance cutoff parameter () to mitigate some of these concerns. The RRAalgorithm proceeds identically to RRA, but only considers the P-values of the gRNAs whose signals are “significant” by an external criterion for the purposes of target-level scoring.

gCrisprTools and MAGeCK differ as follows:

  1. Normalization may be handled differently by the two algorithms. gCrisprTools requires the user to explicitly normalize the data, and defaults to median scaling in automated cases (e.g., in Expression Plot). Similarly, by default gCrisprTools removes guides with low abundance in the control samples from consideration prior to analysis while MAGeCK does not.

  2. gRNA P-values are calculated differently, as described below. Briefly, gCrisprTools assigns significance on the basis of the t-statistics returned by voom/limma’s linear modelling framework, while MAGeCK assigns significance by comparing the observed gRNA counts to the PMF of the Negative Binomial distribution estimated for that gRNA.

  3. The default nominal cutoff is different in the two approaches. This is a trivial difference because the specific choice of does not have a strong effect on the results within a reasonable range, however, and the individual P-value estimates across methods are not comparable anyway.

  4. In the RRAstep, MAGeCK uses the nominal P-values to rank the gRNAs and to check against to disqualify invariant guides. In practice we find that the rankings of P-value point estimates can be unreliable because they summarize both variance and effect size information, and because the null distribution is often not well estimated when differences in abundance are large. By default, gCrisprTools ranks gRNAs on the basis of their fold change, and disqualifies guides on the basis of their one-sided P.

MAGeCK and gCrisprTools Rank Targets Similarly

At the gene level, gCrisprTools (based on voom/limma and Robust Rank Aggregation) largely returns similar P-values to those estimated by MAGeCK, although some variation is present between the point estimates for individual genes. MAGeCK also tends to systematically assign more significance to target-level signals.

This trend is clearer when we view the ranked P-values against each other- the ranking of individual targets is similar across methods, but P-values are somewhat inflated in the MAGeCK implementation relative to gCrisprTools. Notably, MAGeCK appears to identify a number of genes with weak to moderate signals that gCrisprTools eliminates from consideration completely, suggesting that the underlying gRNA P-values are differently estimated by gCrisprTools and MAGeCK (see below).

Nevertheless, the high-priority target rankings are similar. There is a set of targets that both methods identify as equivalently optimal hits (dot in the lower left corner), and targets that are top ranked in one method are always within the very top ranks of the other. By construction, gCrisprTools assigns a P-value of 1 to targets whose associated gRNAs all fail to meet the cutoff, whereas MAGeCK assigns them uniform values along the unit interval- this means that a larger number of targets are bottom ranked by gCrisprTools than MAGeCK.

MAGeCK Estimates gRNA P-values Differently

The differences in target prioritization between MAGeCK and gCrisprTools are largely driven by differences in the gRNA P-value estimation. Generally speaking, the standard Negative Binomial model employed by MAGeCK produces relatively smaller P-values for gRNAs with very large or very small effects.

This is likely to be a consequence of the manner in which each algorithm calculates one-sided statistics; gCrisprTools estimates gRNA-level P-values from the t-statistics derived from the relevant coefficient estimate of the linear model, whereas MAGeCK performs a direct test using the probability mass function of the estimated Negative Binomial distribution. It’s not completely clear which of these approaches is generally superior, but constructing the statistics from the linear model framework is largely consistent using either log transform/PWM estimation or counts-based modeling to identify differences in gRNA abundance.

And consequently we see similar trends when comparing MAGeCK’s gRNA P-values to tailed values derived from DESeq2, which also explicitly models gRNA counts.

Practical Consequences

In practice, this means that certain patterns of gRNA behavior are favored by MAGeCK more than gCrisprTools and vise-versa. It is worth noting that the following examples are largely edge cases, and the difference in target P-value ranks (as opposed to point estimates) is typically relatively slight.

MAGeCK tends to prefer targets with persistent weak signals.

gCrisprTools somewhat upweights targets associated with a few strong signals that might have elevated variances or weaker signals in some of the associated gRNAs (note the difference in Y-axis scale relative to the hits above).

Combined Scoring

In both MAGeCK and gCrisprTools, target-level scores are assigned by generating a rank statistic with the gRNA signals after eliminating all gRNAs that are not ‘significantly’ altered in the screen. MAGeCK uses the same statistic for both ranking and significance testing, but by default gCrisprTools ranks gRNAs by fold change and only uses the P-value estimates for disqualifying guides. Empirically, this approach seems to produce a more stable ranking, and gCrisprTools consequently prioritizes a number of targets with weaker signals and/or larger variances; these are generally not strong candidates in the MAGeCK framework.

The above examples are both genes known to play roles in cellular proliferation, and are consequently likely to be true hits in this example.
